title: Vyoma Orders First Debris Monitoring Satellites For New Constellation
summary: Vyoma, a pioneering German startup focused on space debris monitoring, has entered into a strategic partnership with Bulgarian cubesat specialist EnduroSat to develop a constellation of pilot satellites aimed at tracking and cataloging space debris in low Earth orbit (LEO).

title: Dish Network plots two-way fixed broadband services in Ku-band
summary: Dish Network is seeking permission to use 12 GHz spectrum for fixed terrestrial broadband in the United States, three months after regulators rejected plans for mobile services in the band following interference concerns from Starlink and other satellite operators.

title: NASA Lunar Flashlight Mission Failed Due To Clogged Propellant Lines
summary: NASA's Lunar Flashlight mission aimed to place a cubesat into lunar orbit to search for water ice in the moon's shadowed craters, was hindered by the blockage of propellant lines for the spacecraft's thrusters.

title: DCubed reveals in-space manufacturing demonstration
summary: DCubed, a German startup specializing in deployable satellite structures, plans to conduct an in-space manufacturing demonstration later this year.

title: Axiom Space & ESA To Launch Polish Astronaut On Future Mission
summary: Axiom Space and the European Space Agency (ESA), have signed an agreement to send an ESA astronaut from Poland into space through an upcoming Axiom Space mission. Specific details about the mission and the identity of the Polish astronaut will be formally disclosed at a later point, pending approval from NASA and its international partners.

title: Northrop Grumman and Firefly’s Antares 330 and MLV plans take shape
summary: As the Cygnus S.S. Laurel Clark spends its first days berthed to the ISS, the successor to the Antares 230+ launch vehicle that launched it is taking shape in the facilities of Northrop Grumman (NG) and Firefly Aerospace.

title: NASA Software Catalog Offers Free Programs for Earth Science, More
summary: Each year, NASA scientists, engineers, and developers create software packages to manage space missions, test spacecraft, and analyze the petabytes of data produced by agency research satellites. As the agency innovates for the benefit of humanity, many of these programs are now downloadable and free of charge through NASA’s Software Catalog.

title: Clogged propellant lines doomed NASA lunar cubesat mission
summary: A NASA lunar cubesat mission failed to go into orbit around the moon earlier this year when debris blocked propellant lines for the spacecraft’s thrusters.
